article.description:
Tangela Smith broke out of her slump
and is hoping the same can be said for the Sacramento Monarchs.
article.headline: Monarchs remain undefeated against Storm
article.linkText: Smith breaks out of slump to lead Monarchs to win
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Tangela Smith broke out of her slump
and is hoping the same can be said for the Sacramento Monarchs.

	   Smith scored 16 of her season-high 20 points in the second half,
and the Monarchs pulled away to a 72-64 victory over the Seattle
Storm on Thursday night.

	   In the absence of injured All-Star center Yolanda Griffith, the
Monarchs have been looking for an inside threat. It hasn't been
Smith, who entered the game averaging 8.9 points.

	   "Everyone has to step up with her (Griffith) out,'' Smith said.
"I need to be more aggressive, be more offensive minded. I can't
get down on myself. I know I can shoot the ball and be a force in
the game.''

	   Kedra Holland-Corn scored 14 points, Lady Grooms had 13 and
Ticha Penicheiro added 11 points, 10 assists and six rebounds for
the Monarchs (2-6), 7-0 all-time against Seattle.

	   "Sacramento is a fine team, I think we caught them when they
were really intent on getting a win,'' Seattle coach Lin Dunn said.

	   Lauren Jackson had 15 points and 11 rebounds for Seattle (4-6),
which has lost three straight games. Reserve Kate Paye, who had not
scored entering the game, made three 3-pointers and finished with
11 points before fouling out in the final minute. Rookie Sue Bird
was held to seven points.

	   The Monarchs made 11 of 14 free throws over the final four
minutes to hold off the Storm.

	   "Tonight was about runs and we had the last one,'' Monarchs
coach Maura McHugh said. "We did not fold this whole game and kept
our mental errors under control.''

	   Smith scored eight straight points for the Monarchs as they took
a 50-39 lead with 12:16 remaining.

	   The Storm responded with a 12-1 run, tying the game at 51-51 on
a free throw by Simone Edwards with 8:27 left. The Monarchs
responded by scoring six straight points, including a 3-pointer by
Ruthie Bolton, to take the lead for good.

	   "We didn't do a good job on our post defense,'' Dunn said. "We
didn't keep Smith from getting some easy touches and that helped
them build the lead. We had to fight very hard to get it close
after that.''
